This is a simple in-place filtering problem using two pointers.

Idea

Use pointer k to track position for valid elements.

Traverse the array:

If nums[i] != val, place it at index k and increment k.

Ignore elements equal to val.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1)

C++ Code
class Solution {
public:
    int removeElement(vector<int>& nums, int val) {
        int k = 0;
        
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++){
            if(nums[i] != val){
                nums[k++] = nums[i];
            }
        }
        
        return k;
    }
};
Example

Input
nums = [3,2,2,3], val = 3

Process:

Skip 3

Keep 2, 2

Array becomes:

[2,2,_,_]

Output
k = 2

💡 Alternate trick (faster when many vals present)
Swap with last element:

If nums[i] == val, replace it with last element and reduce size.

Do not increment i in that case.
